      "modified": "1970-01-01T00:00:00.014Z",
      "body": [
        {
          "type": "TextualBody",
          "value": "**The rosettes foldout** (despite the filename — this isn't bathing figures, it's the famous nine-rosette diagram from the manuscript's largest fold-out leaf). Nine separate circular figures arrayed across a single sheet, connected by faintly drawn lines and rendered with patterns of dots, stars, petals, and miniature human figures. The most enigmatic page in the codex.",
          "purpose": "commenting"
        }
      ],
      "archie:hasHistory": "https://archie.demo/voynich/annotations/history/000000000EQ8P7Q1GNC5HNBJEH.json"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://archie.demo/voynich/annotations/000000000F9SEBRPD87G4EG92S/v1",
      "type": "Annotation",
      "target": {
        "type": "SpecificResource",
        "source": "https://archie.demo/voynich/canvas/o4",
        "selector": {
          "type": "FragmentSelector",
          "conformsTo": "http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/",
          "value": "xywh=pixel:500,280,510,530"
        }
      },
      "modified": "1970-01-01T00:00:00.015Z",
      "body": [
        {
          "type": "TextualBody",
          "value": "**The central rosette.** The largest figure on the foldout — concentric rings with a band of small bell-shaped figures around the inner disk and a label band that wraps the whole structure. Many readers have proposed it represents the centre of the cosmos, a city plan, a wind rose, or a botanical fruiting body; none of those readings has come close to consensus.",
          "purpose": "commenting"
        }
      ],
      "archie:hasHistory": "https://archie.demo/voynich/annotations/history/000000000F9SEBRPD87G4EG92S.json"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://archie.demo/voynich/annotations/000000000GJSGT3G0C92PCM8AW/v1",
      "type": "Annotation",
      "target": {
        "type": "SpecificResource",
        "source": "https://archie.demo/voynich/canvas/o4",
        "selector": {
          "type": "FragmentSelector",
          "conformsTo": "http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/",
          "value": "xywh=pixel:50,30,430,380"
        }
      },
      "modified": "1970-01-01T00:00:00.016Z",
      "body": [
        {
          "type": "TextualBody",
          "value": "**Top-left ring with star centre.** An open ring populated by small radiating tooth-figures, with a star-burst at the centre. The ring is not labelled; the visual rhyme with star-charts has prompted some readers to call it a celestial diagram, but no positional astronomy correlates with the placement of the figures around the ring.",
          "purpose": "commenting"
        }
      ],
      "archie:hasHistory": "https://archie.demo/voynich/annotations/history/000000000GJSGT3G0C92PCM8AW.json"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://archie.demo/voynich/annotations/000000000HR9QJA0339YF8PT2T/v1",
      "type": "Annotation",
      "target": {
        "type": "SpecificResource",
        "source": "https://archie.demo/voynich/canvas/o4",
        "selector": {
          "type": "FragmentSelector",
          "conformsTo": "http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/",
          "value": "xywh=pixel:50,620,430,440"
        }
      },
      "modified": "1970-01-01T00:00:00.017Z",
      "body": [
        {
          "type": "TextualBody",
          "value": "**Lower-left rosette with figures.** A complex circle showing what appear to be small standing figures arranged around a patterned central disk. Unlike the other rosettes on this folio, this one carries embedded human forms — a feature it shares with the balneological quire, which has led to the hypothesis that the rosettes summarise content distributed elsewhere in the manuscript.",
          "purpose": "commenting"
        }
      ],
      "archie:hasHistory": "https://archie.demo/voynich/annotations/history/000000000HR9QJA0339YF8PT2T.json"
    },
